This ex·- traordinary rigour was justified, in some measure, by its salutary consequences; smee, after a scrutiny of seventeen days, not a com- plaint or abuse could be found in the court or city: and it might be alleged that the Greeks could be ruled only with a rod of iron, and that the public interest is the motive and law of the supreme judge. Yet in the crime, or the suspicion, of treason, that judge is of all others the most credulous and partial.
